h3. Summary
When the issue has a significant number of attachments (e.g., ~90+ or ~70+ large size files (>40MB)), it's not possible to download the attachments.

h3. Environment
Jira issues with ~90 attachments or more or issues with more than 70 larger files (>40MB).

h3. Steps to reproduce
* Create an issue and add more than 70 attachments to it;
* Open the issue in the new issue view;
* Try to download the attachment;

h3. Expected results
It will be possible to download the files.

h3. Actual result
When clicking on the attachment, nothing will happen. However, looking at the dev tool in the browser, the user will encounter a 431 status code for the download request.


h3. Workaround
* Reduce the number of attachments or split in different tickets;
* Download the files using the old issue view;

Hello,

Would love to have a feature to notify our helpdesk users on their mobile phone through the Jira mobile app when new issues gets created.

 

*Workaround*

Go to your Project Settings ->  Project Automation -> New Rule 

( For next-gen project automation is under project settings -> Apps -> Project Automation)

Create an automation rule when an issue is created and applies to the rules that you want and just put a comment in the ticket mentioning you. This will trigger a push notification to your phone and an in-app notification. 

To mention you in the ticket you need to follow this format:
{code:java}
  [~accountid:<<account_id>>] {code}
Make sure to replace *<<account_id>>*  with the user's Account ID that you want to notify.

You can find this by going to Jira Administration > Users, then clicking on the User you want to notify, The final part of the URL after /users/ will be the user's Account ID or using the REST API endpoint below:
{code:java}
 curl --request GET \
--url 'https://xxxxxx.atlassian.net/rest/api/3/groupuserpicker?query=user@domain.com' \
--user 'admin@domain.com:A1b2345CdEfgHIJkLMn67OPQ' \
--header 'Accept: application/json'{code}
Also, you can use the one below directly on the browser:
{code:java}
 https://xxxxxx.atlassian.net/rest/api/latest/user/search?query=user@domain.com{code}

When creating issues from a specific period of days, the equal operator "=" is not clearly documented on how it should work. For example, searching for issues created five days ago
{code:java}
createdDate = startOfDay(-5){code}
doesn't return desired results, whereas 
{code:java}
createdDate < startOfDay(-5) and createdDate > startOfDay(-6) {code}
deliver the expected results. However, reading the documentation, there isn't a clear example on how to use the "=" operator. 

Original documentation:
* [Advanced searching - functions reference - *startOfDay()*|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirasoftwarecloud/advanced-searching-functions-reference-764478342.html#Advancedsearching-functionsreference-startOfDaystartOfDay()]
